\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 The Unfair Advantage\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Most people trying to sell AI services don't actually understand how to use AI well. They've used ChatGPT a few times and think they're experts.\
If you actually invest time in learning prompt engineering\'97experimenting with different approaches, understanding how to structure prompts, learning what works across different tools\'97you'll be legitimately more competent than 90% of the market.\
This is a temporary arbitrage opportunity. In 2-3 years, AI tools will get better at understanding vague prompts, or prompt engineering will become common knowledge.\
But right now, in 2025, there's a genuine skill gap. People who can bridge that gap can earn money from it.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Common Pitfalls\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Pitfall 1: Selling generic, untested prompts
\f0\b0  If you just copy prompts from Reddit and resell them, customers will notice and leave bad reviews. Test everything thoroughly.\

\f1\b Pitfall 2: Overpromising results
\f0\b0  AI is powerful but not magic. Don't promise it will "10x" someone's business. Promise time savings and efficiency improvements.\

\f1\b Pitfall 3: Not specializing
\f0\b0  "Prompts for everyone!" = "Prompts for no one." Pick a niche. Serve them specifically.\

\f1\b Pitfall 4: Ignoring the human part of consulting
\f0\b0  Clients hiring consultants want guidance and reassurance as much as technical prompts. Don't just email them a doc and disappear.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Starting This Week\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

